{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ca370049-cecc-47b7-9ba1-975fa9e8a636","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find the process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### To get the file off the pod\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nThis gives real-time CPU %, GC, thread pool stats — useful before committing to a full trace.\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails due to network restrictions, copy the tools into the container image at build time, or use `kubectl cp` to push the tool binaries in.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1d63fb03-9486-4a6c-a860-160ba210f2fc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":414,"requestId":"ABC6:24FEAD:13D88D5:163F140:6A067024"},"id":"0e91d2cc-e31f-487c-92eb-a0c9606bf8ae","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:00:31.699Z","parentId":"039889e8-b318-48f9-808c-892b4aec021f"}
